<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEACHING ABSTINENCE TO PREVENT AIDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is hard to argue with the concept of sexual abstinence as the most important 
means of preventing AIDS, but to insist on celibacy as the only formula for 
teaching teen-agers about this dread disease indicates a tenuous grip on 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
True enough, celibacy will absolutely prevent all sexually transmitted 
diseases, but that begs the question of how to handle those who can't seem to 
resist the raging torrent of adolescent hormones. 
</P>
<P>
I suppose this same group of parents would prohibit teaching about the dangers 
of drunk driving because, after all, their sons and daughters will obviously 
not imbibe before the age of 21. 
</P>
<P>
ROBERT E. GOYETTE, MD, Rolling Hills Estates 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
