<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHOOL REPORT; 
</P>
<P>
ANTI-PREJUDICE POLICY REAFFIRMED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENISE HAMILTON , News from the L.A. Unified School District board meeting. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Responding to complaints that children of Middle Eastern ancestry have been 
subjected to racial slurs, the board on Monday reaffirmed a policy approved two 
years ago condemning prejudice. 
</P>
<P>
A resolution asks that all school employees combat prejudice and encourage 
open, accurate discussions about events in the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
School board President Jackie Goldberg said that students who call others names 
may be required to write essays on the importance of treating all individuals 
with respect or to attend group discussions about tolerance. 
</P>
<P>
The board also: 
</P>
<P>
Gave tentative approval to a proposal establishing a mobile Ben &amp; Jerry's 
Ice Cream store to be managed and operated by Manual Arts High School students 
at USC. Students will be responsible for all phases of the business and profits 
will go to the high school. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
FUTURE FILE 
</P>
<P>
FITNESS: The board will consider a proposal by board member Mark Slavkin to 
seek private funding for physical fitness and health education programs. 
Slavkin has cited the poor showing of district youngsters on state physical 
fitness tests and wants the district to seek funding for private programs that 
supplement regular physical education classes. 
</P>
<P>
Classroom Capsule 
</P>
<P>
Of the district's 625,000 students, more than 213,300 speak little or no 
English. The vast majority speak Spanish, but at least 82 other languages are 
spoken. Fewer than 6,000 of the district's 30,000 teachers are trained to teach 
in languages other than English. DENISE HAMILTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
