<HEADLINE>
<P>
GROUP CLAIMS 7 BROKE LAW ON CAMPAIGN GIFTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA FRITZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Responding to a Los Angeles Times story, Common Cause has filed a complaint 
with the Federal Election Commission accusing seven wealthy campaign 
contributors of violating a federal election law that prohibits anyone from 
making more than $25,000 a year in contributions to federal candidates. 
</P>
<P>
In a letter to FEC Chairwoman Lee Ann Elliott, Common Cause President Fred 
Wertheimer called on the commission to "take appropriate action against these 
individuals and to institute procedures by which the FEC can regularly detect 
such violations." 
</P>
<P>
The Times reported in a story published April 18 that the FEC had failed to 
take action against at least 10 wealthy men and women who appeared to have 
exceeded the limit on contributions during 1988. 
</P>
<P>
The seven contributors named in the Common Cause complaint were corporate 
buy-out specialists Henry R. Kravis, Ronald O. Perelman and Harold Simmons; 
Kravis' father, Raymond; Ira Riklis, son of corporate raider Meshulam Riklis; 
Dwayne O. Andreas, chairman of Archer Daniels Midland, and his wife, Dorothy 
Inez. 
</P>
<P>
The three others named in the Times story were Meshulam Riklis, New York 
developer Donald Trump and Rose Hunt, heir to the Hunt oil fortune. Common 
Cause did not explain why these names were not included in the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
FEC officials have acknowledged that they do not adequately monitor compliance 
with the limits on campaign spending. Although a few people have been fined in 
the past for exceeding these limits, the penalties levied in these cases have 
not exceeded $250. 
</P>
<P>
Wertheimer noted that both the Times story and the Common Cause complaint were 
drawn from candidate reports currently on file at the FEC headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
Under federal election law, contributors are permitted to give up to $2,000 to 
a congressional campaign, $5,000 a year to a political action committee and 
$20,000 a year to a party committee. But total contributions in any calendar 
year may not exceed $25,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ELECTION LAWS; POLITICAL CONTRIBUTIONS; POLITICAL CANDIDATES; FEDERAL ELECTION 
COMMISSION; FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE; WEALTHY PEOPLE 
</P>
