<P>
CLEMSON TO PLAY IN TAMPA BOWL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CLEMSON, S.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 18th-ranked Clemson Tigers have accepted an invitation to play in the Hall 
of Fame Bowl in Tampa, Fla., on New Year's Day, two newspapers reported today. 
</P>
<P>
The Tigers, 8-2 under first-year Coach Ken Hatfield, will probably take on 
either Michigan or Illinois in the bowl. 
</P>
<P>
Bowl bids do not go out officially until Nov. 24. 
</P>
<P>
In opting for the Hall of Fame Bowl, the Tigers turned down a chance to play in 
the inaugural Blockbuster Bowl, which pays up to $1.4 million as opposed to $1 
million for the Hall of Fame. But other factors figured in Clemson's decision, 
according to both the News of Greenville and the State of Columbia. Clemson 
apparently wanted to play on New Year's Day and on national television. The 
Hall of Fame is on Jan. 1 and will be televised by NBC. The Blockbuster is on 
Dec. 28 and will be shown by Raycom. 
