<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: ANTIBIOTICS, BISMUTH FOUND HELPFUL IN TREATING ULCERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON AND TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I have been taking Tagamet for a couple of years to treat ulcers. 
Unfortunately, when I stop the medicine, my stomach soon starts to hurt and the 
ulcer returns. 
</P>
<P>
I remember reading something in your column about a new approach to curing 
ulcers. My doctor is skeptical. But if there is really a way to cure ulcers, 
I'd rather be done with them once and for all than take Tagamet for the rest of 
my life. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: A controversy over the causes of stomach ulcers has raged for several 
years. Many gastroenterologists doubted that ulcers could be infectious. 
However, a consensus is growing that many ulcers are due to bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
At the World Congress of Gastroenterology, Helicobacter pylori was recognized 
as a major cause of ulcers. Treating with acid-suppressing drugs such as 
antacids, Tagamet (cimetidine), or Zantac (ranitidine) can help heal the 
lesion, but ulcers return in up to 80% of patients when the medicine is 
discontinued. 
</P>
<P>
Treatment with antibiotics and bismuth (Pepto-Bismol) appears to be much more 
successful in eliminating the bug. Dr. Barry Marshall of the University of 
Virginia, quoted in Medical World News, says, "We think we have a cure for this 
bacterium and thus a cure for ulcer disease in probably 90% of patients." 
</P>
<P>
Q: I used to take tryptophan to help me get to sleep, especially when I 
traveled. Ever since the ban I have had to rely on non-prescription drugs, 
which I don't like as well. 
</P>
<P>
I am getting fed up with the government. It seems like a long time has gone by, 
and I haven't heard anything about the cause of the tryptophan problem. Will 
tryptophan become available again? 
</P>
<P>
A: We too are disappointed that the investigation of this problem has gone so 
slowly. Over a year ago the first reports of a rare blood disease called 
eosinophilia myalgia syndrome (EMS) came to the FDA's attention. People 
developed fatigue, fever and severe muscle pain, and some died. 
</P>
<P>
The outbreak was traced to l-tryptophan. Investigators have linked EMS to a new 
manufacturing process developed by one Japanese supplier, and the company has 
recently identified the component associated with the epidemic. 
</P>
<P>
We don't understand why the FDA has not kept the public better informed about 
its progress in this investigation. If contamination from a single source was 
the cause of the problem, it seems reasonable to expect that eventually 
tryptophan could be sold to the public again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110690-0194 </DOCNO>
